## 4. Technical Root Cause
[cite_start]The incident was triggered by a runaway file-writing process that generated multiple 500MB dummy files in the `/tmp/incident-test/` directory. [cite: 14]

In a production environment, this mimics:
* [cite_start]**Log Rotation Failure:** Logs accumulating without being purged. [cite: 16]
* [cite_start]**Unconstrained Backups:** Local backup jobs writing to the root partition. [cite: 17]
* [cite_start]**Application Errors:** Temporary files from crashed processes failing to clear. [cite: 18]

---

## 5. Investigation & Remediation

### Diagnostic Path
I utilized the following commands to isolate the issue:
1. [cite_start]**Initial Check:** `df -h` to identify the saturated mount point. [cite: 22]
2. [cite_start]**Directory Analysis:** `du -h / --max-depth=2 | sort -rh` to locate the largest directories. [cite: 25]
3. [cite_start]**Deep Dive:** `ls -lh /tmp/incident-test/` to confirm the presence of large, unauthorized files. [cite: 29]

### Recovery Action
| Step | Action | Command |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Locate culprit files | [cite_start]`du -sh /tmp/*` [cite: 34] |
| 2 | Immediate Remediation | [cite_start]`rm -rf /tmp/incident-test/` [cite: 34] |
| 3 | Verify Recovery | [cite_start]`df -h /` [cite: 34] |

